{"name":"Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Adjunction.AdjointFunctorTheorems","instances":[],"imports":["Init","Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Generator","Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Limits.ConeCategory","Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Limits.Constructions.WeaklyInitial","Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Limits.FunctorCategory","Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Subobject.Comma"],"declarations":[{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.lean#L144-L148","name":"CategoryTheory.Limits.hasLimits_of_hasColimits_of_isSeparating","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.html#CategoryTheory.Limits.hasLimits_of_hasColimits_of_isSeparating","doc":"A consequence of the special adjoint functor theorem: if `C` is cocomplete, well-copowered and\nhas a small separating set, then it is complete. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.lean#L135-L139","name":"CategoryTheory.Limits.hasColimits_of_hasLimits_of_isCoseparating","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.html#CategoryTheory.Limits.hasColimits_of_hasLimits_of_isCoseparating","doc":"A consequence of the special adjoint functor theorem: if `C` is complete, well-powered and\nhas a small coseparating set, then it is cocomplete. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.lean#L121-L126","name":"CategoryTheory.isLeftAdjointOfPreservesColimitsOfIsSeparatig","kind":"def","docLink":"./Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.html#CategoryTheory.isLeftAdjointOfPreservesColimitsOfIsSeparatig","doc":"The special adjoint functor theorem: if `F : C ⥤ D` preserves colimits and `C` is cocomplete,\nwell-copowered and has a small separating set, then `F` has a right adjoint.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.lean#L110-L115","name":"CategoryTheory.isRightAdjointOfPreservesLimitsOfIsCoseparating","kind":"def","docLink":"./Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.html#CategoryTheory.isRightAdjointOfPreservesLimitsOfIsCoseparating","doc":"The special adjoint functor theorem: if `G : D ⥤ C` preserves limits and `D` is complete,\nwell-powered and has a small coseparating set, then `G` has a left adjoint.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.lean#L86-L98","name":"CategoryTheory.isRightAdjointOfPreservesLimitsOfSolutionSetCondition","kind":"def","docLink":"./Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.html#CategoryTheory.isRightAdjointOfPreservesLimitsOfSolutionSetCondition","doc":"The general adjoint functor theorem says that if `G : D ⥤ C` preserves limits and `D` has them,\nif `G` satisfies the solution set condition then `G` is a right adjoint.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.lean#L74-L80","name":"CategoryTheory.solutionSetCondition_of_isRightAdjoint","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.html#CategoryTheory.solutionSetCondition_of_isRightAdjoint","doc":"If `G : D ⥤ C` is a right adjoint it satisfies the solution set condition.  "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.lean#L61-L64","name":"CategoryTheory.SolutionSetCondition","kind":"def","docLink":"./Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Adjunction/AdjointFunctorTheorems.html#CategoryTheory.SolutionSetCondition","doc":"The functor `G : D ⥤ C` satisfies the *solution set condition* if for every `A : C`, there is a\nfamily of morphisms `{f_i : A ⟶ G (B_i) // i ∈ ι}` such that given any morphism `h : A ⟶ G X`,\nthere is some `i ∈ ι` such that `h` factors through `f_i`.\n\nThe key part of this definition is that the indexing set `ι` lives in `Type v`, where `v` is the\nuniverse of morphisms of the category: this is the \"smallness\" condition which allows the general\nadjoint functor theorem to go through.\n"}]}